00:47:22,100 --> 00:47:23,800
and had put this chap away for life.

1049
00:47:23,800 --> 00:47:26,250
But he'd escaped, and was after revenge.

1050
00:47:26,250 --> 00:47:31,250
Just then, out of nowhere, a
bat appeared, flying at me.

1051
00:47:31,280 --> 00:47:34,550
I thought how wonderful it
would be to be like a bat,

1052
00:47:34,550 --> 00:47:36,630
prowling the night streets,

1053
00:47:36,630 --> 00:47:39,743
bringing light to the
darkest corners of society.

1054
00:47:40,590 --> 00:47:45,570
Then, out of nowhere, appeared
a documentary filmmaker.

1055
00:47:45,570 --> 00:47:46,620
He was trying to get material

1056
00:47:46,620 --> 00:47:48,740
for a documentary on crime and criminals.

1057
00:47:48,740 --> 00:47:51,740
From that moment on, my fate was decided.

1058
00:47:51,740 --> 00:47:54,830
I was to be a documentary filmmaker.

1059
00:47:54,830 --> 00:47:56,470
I started close to home.

1060
00:47:56,470 --> 00:47:59,730
I documented everything
in my own life first.

1061
00:47:59,730 --> 00:48:00,763
My confirmation.

1062
00:48:02,000 --> 00:48:04,560
My last day of public school.

1063
00:48:04,560 --> 00:48:06,320
Even my loss of virginity.

1064
00:48:06,320 --> 00:48:08,780
Well, at least the prelude
to my loss of virginity,

1065
00:48:08,780 --> 00:48:10,020
though I was able to reenact

1066
00:48:10,020 --> 00:48:11,750
the entire event for the camera later,

1067
00:48:11,750 --> 00:48:14,400
after the subject became more comfortable.

1068
00:48:14,400 --> 00:48:16,500
I've always made documentaries.

1069
00:48:16,500 --> 00:48:17,840
It's my destiny.

1070
00:48:17,840 --> 00:48:19,360
- It's a mania, George.

1071
00:48:19,360 --> 00:48:20,270
- It's a calling.

1072
00:48:20,270 --> 00:48:22,850
- Many are called, but
few answer the phone.

1073
00:48:22,850 --> 00:48:25,009
That's what all the filmmakers
here have in common.

1074
00:48:25,009 --> 00:48:26,350
- What, a death wish?

1075
00:48:26,350 --> 00:48:27,760
- No.

1076
00:48:27,760 --> 00:48:29,720
There's a reason why no one
here's removed their film,

1077
00:48:29,720 --> 00:48:31,450
despite the risk.

1078
00:48:31,450 --> 00:48:34,180
We all have a passion to make
movies, maybe not talent,

1079
00:48:34,180 --> 00:48:38,003
but passion, a need that
drives us to take stupid risks.

1080
00:48:39,190 --> 00:48:41,650
Not many people can understand that.

1081
00:48:41,650 --> 00:48:43,120
- I can.

1082
00:48:43,120 --> 00:48:46,200
- That's because you have
the same mania, George.

1083
00:48:46,200 --> 00:48:49,210
But, then, I've always
been drawn to maniacs.

1084
00:48:49,210 --> 00:48:50,057
- So have I.

1085
00:48:52,120 --> 00:48:52,953
- I have to go.

1086
00:48:54,660 --> 00:48:56,660
- Will you be coming to the costume party?

1087
00:48:56,660 --> 00:48:58,090
- I wouldn't miss it.

1088
00:48:58,090 --> 00:49:00,990
People reveal themselves through
the costumes they choose.

1089
00:49:03,670 --> 00:49:06,615
- Well, um, not always.

1090
00:49:06,615 --> 00:49:09,198
(party music)

1091
00:49:14,947 --> 00:49:16,670
- [George Voiceover] That
night was the festival

1092
00:49:16,670 --> 00:49:18,720
costume party, which all the filmmakers

1093
00:49:18,720 --> 00:49:20,120
were supposed to attend,

1094
00:49:20,120 --> 00:49:23,103
and I was going to seize the
opportunity that it presented.

1095
00:49:28,590 --> 00:49:30,730
We spotted trouble coming our way,

1096
00:49:30,730 --> 00:49:33,030
trouble in a red suit and a white beard

1097
00:49:33,030 --> 00:49:34,963
with a sack full of dangerous goodies.

1098
00:49:42,768 --> 00:49:44,935
- I got something for you.

1099
00:49:53,490 --> 00:49:55,183
I was a guerilla once too.

1100
00:50:03,399 --> 00:50:06,316
(party horns wail)

1101
00:50:08,166 --> 00:50:09,374
- [George] There she is.

1102
00:50:09,374 --> 00:50:10,820
- Who?
- The chicken.

1103
00:50:10,820 --> 00:50:13,260
But I must be certain.

1104
00:50:13,260 --> 00:50:16,710
- You know, it'll never
work between you two.

1105
00:50:16,710 --> 00:50:18,067
You're too different.

1106
00:50:34,650 --> 00:50:36,650
Of course, this must have been 1984

1107
00:50:36,650 --> 00:50:39,480
when I was secretary of
the interior, which...

1108
00:50:40,500 --> 00:50:41,333
What the hell?

1109
00:50:41,333 --> 00:50:42,922
You spoiled my rap on the devil, man.

1110
00:50:42,922 --> 00:50:43,920
- It's her.

1111
00:50:43,920 --> 00:50:46,210
I'm gonna sneak into her editing
room and look at her film.

1112
00:50:46,210 --> 00:50:48,300
Try to keep her here as long as you can.

1113
00:50:48,300 --> 00:50:50,550
- Too late, there goes
your little chickadee.

1114
00:50:52,850 --> 00:50:53,683
- Damn.

1115
00:50:55,600 --> 00:50:56,433
Hey!

1116
00:50:56,433 --> 00:50:57,266
Hey!

1117
00:50:58,490 --> 00:51:00,220
I love your costume.

1118
00:51:00,220 --> 00:51:02,893
It really, um, highlights your figure.

1119
00:51:05,920 --> 00:51:09,180
- I don't quite know how to
respond to that, Mr. Sand.

1120
00:51:09,180 --> 00:51:10,053
- Oh, sorry.

1121
00:51:11,160 --> 00:51:13,350
I mistook you for another chicken.

1122
00:51:13,350 --> 00:51:15,420
- Yes, I suppose you think

1123
00:51:15,420 --> 00:51:17,320
we chickens all look alike, don't you?

1124
00:51:22,388 --> 00:51:23,900
- [George Voiceover]
As for what came next,

1125
00:51:23,900 --> 00:51:27,313
I can't say I'm proud of
it, but it was necessary.

1126
00:51:28,633 --> 00:51:31,550
(suspicious music)

1127
00:52:03,052 --> 00:52:06,302
(door handle rattling)

1128
00:52:25,551 --> 00:52:27,968
(card snaps)

1129
00:52:47,971 --> 00:52:50,471
(lock clicks)

1130
00:53:01,527 --> 00:53:05,293
(editing table turns on)

1131
00:53:06,568 --> 00:53:10,068
- [Woman] With this elephant, I thee kill.

1132
00:53:11,265 --> 00:53:13,481
- [George] Oh, my God.

1133
00:53:13,481 --> 00:53:16,045
(door clacks)

1134
00:53:16,045 --> 00:53:17,952
(editing table turns off)

1135
00:53:17,952 --> 00:53:20,869
(suspicious music)

1136
00:53:32,407 --> 00:53:34,370
- [George Voiceover] I was
so unnerved by what I'd seen

1137
00:53:34,370 --> 00:53:37,675
that I hardly paid attention
to the next day's film.

1138
00:53:37,675 --> 00:53:40,399
(angsty music)

1139
00:53:40,399 --> 00:53:41,699
(Holden sighs)

1140
00:53:41,699 --> 00:53:43,380
- [Holden Voiceover] My name is Holden.

1141
00:53:43,380 --> 00:53:44,543
Holden Samsa.

1142
00:53:46,610 --> 00:53:49,200
My roommate Stradbater
always got the chicks.

1143
00:53:49,200 --> 00:53:51,950
He was a handsome bastard, and he knew it.

1144
00:53:51,950 --> 00:53:53,740
I couldn't help but wonder
what he would look like

1145
00:53:53,740 --> 00:53:54,740
with his throat cut.

1146
00:54:05,080 --> 00:54:06,803
- [Rosemary] I have to go, Mr. Wong.

1147
00:54:07,987 --> 00:54:10,840
- I'm sorry, I didn't mean to
interrupt your conversation.

1148
00:54:10,840 --> 00:54:12,510
- Oh, it's not your fault.

1149
00:54:12,510 --> 00:54:14,200
That girl has been on pins and needles

1150
00:54:14,200 --> 00:54:16,020
ever since Maria was killed.

1151
00:54:16,020 --> 00:54:17,550
- I heard her mention your son's name.

1152
00:54:17,550 --> 00:54:19,370
Were she and Mike close?

1153
00:54:19,370 --> 00:54:23,260
- Yes, she and my son were quite close.

1154
00:54:23,260 --> 00:54:27,070
Because of that, I recused
myself from judging her film.

1155
00:54:27,070 --> 00:54:28,130
I didn't want anyone to think

1156
00:54:28,130 --> 00:54:30,500
that favoritism could be involved.

1157
00:54:30,500 --> 00:54:32,690
- Is there anyone else around
who worked on your son's film,

1158
00:54:32,690 --> 00:54:34,650
besides the other finalists?

1159
00:54:34,650 --> 00:54:35,970
I have some questions.

1160
00:54:35,970 --> 00:54:38,240
- Well, there's Elliot Lewis,

1161
00:54:38,240 --> 00:54:40,100
who's one of the judges this year.

1162
00:54:40,100 --> 00:54:43,030
He was the assistant
director on Mike's film.

1163
00:54:43,030 --> 00:54:45,060
- Yeah, I worked on that film.

1164
00:54:45,060 --> 00:54:48,780
It was a very difficult shoot,
even before Mike was killed.

1165
00:54:48,780 --> 00:54:50,600
- [George] What do you mean?

1166
00:54:50,600 --> 00:54:54,620
- Well, Mike drove the
crew hard, and Rosemary,

1167
00:54:54,620 --> 00:54:57,140
Rosemary Olsen, she was the key grip,

1168
00:54:57,140 --> 00:55:00,070
that's the person who pushes the dolly,

1169
00:55:00,070 --> 00:55:02,940
well, she didn't exactly
know what she was doing,

1170
00:55:02,940 --> 00:55:06,240
so every dolly shot took twice
as long as it should have.

1171
00:55:06,240 --> 00:55:07,720
People said Mike only let her do it

1172
00:55:07,720 --> 00:55:11,213
because they were, you know.

1173
00:55:12,920 --> 00:55:15,560
Anyway, as always happens on
films, they started to fight,

1174
00:55:15,560 --> 00:55:18,070
more and more as the film went along.

1175
00:55:18,070 --> 00:55:20,213
And then that fateful day came.

1176
00:55:22,690 --> 00:55:25,900
- Go on, and please look
at me, not at the camera.

1177
00:55:25,900 --> 00:55:27,550
- Oh.

1178
00:55:27,550 --> 00:55:28,383
Sorry.

1179
00:55:30,120 --> 00:55:32,160
Anyway, Mike always liked dolly shots,

1180
00:55:32,160 --> 00:55:33,520
he liked the camera moving.

1181
00:55:33,520 --> 00:55:35,060
The faster the better.

1182
00:55:35,060 --> 00:55:36,190
So, on this one shot,

1183
00:55:36,190 --> 00:55:38,000
he wanted the dolly to move really fast,

1184
00:55:38,000 --> 00:55:40,430
but no matter how fast
Rosemary would push the dolly,

1185
00:55:40,430 --> 00:55:42,720
Mike would always yell, "Faster!"

1186
00:55:42,720 --> 00:55:45,330
Each time, Mike would stand
between the dolly tracks

1187
00:55:45,330 --> 00:55:46,230
at the beginning of the shot

1188
00:55:46,230 --> 00:55:47,500
to make sure he wasn't in the frame,

1189
00:55:47,500 --> 00:55:50,490
and then step back as
the dolly came around.

1190
00:55:50,490 --> 00:55:54,130
And he'd watch the shot on
this little video monitor.

1191
00:55:54,130 --> 00:55:57,487
Well, finally, Rosemary got
fed up, and she yelled at Mike,

1192
00:55:57,487 --> 00:55:59,600
"You want faster, how's this?!"

1193
00:55:59,600 --> 00:56:01,330
And as the camera flew down the tracks,

1194
00:56:01,330 --> 00:56:03,640
Mike finally looked satisfied.

1195
00:56:03,640 --> 00:56:06,397
He was turning to Rosemary and saying,

1196
00:56:06,397 --> 00:56:08,536
"Yes, that's..."

1197
00:56:08,536 --> 00:56:10,050
(loud thud)

1198
00:56:10,050 --> 00:56:12,500
Doctor said he was dead
before he hit the ground.

1199
00:56:14,170 --> 00:56:15,870
- If Mike died while you were shooting,

1200
00:56:15,870 --> 00:56:16,970
who finished the film?

1201
00:56:18,660 --> 00:56:20,063
- Rosemary, of course.

1202
00:56:22,480 --> 00:56:24,580
It was a wonderful opportunity for her.

1203
00:56:26,220 --> 00:56:27,310
- Thank you, Elliot.

1204
00:56:28,800 --> 00:56:29,700
You can cut, Tori.

1205
00:56:30,870 --> 00:56:32,080
- Oh, pardon me for rushing off,

1206
00:56:32,080 --> 00:56:35,870
but I'm putting the
finishing touches on my film

1207
00:56:35,870 --> 00:56:38,623
and I've only got a few more hours.

1208
00:56:41,630 --> 00:56:43,133
- Double espresso, please.

1209
00:56:44,040 --> 00:56:45,290
Extra bitter.

1210
00:56:45,290 --> 00:56:46,903
- I thought I might find you here.

1211
00:56:48,674 --> 00:56:50,420
- I have nothing to say to you.

1212
00:56:50,420 --> 00:56:52,970
- Your film's entitled "Sinner's Cafe",

1213
00:56:52,970 --> 00:56:55,087
And this is the Sinner's Cafe, after all.

1214
00:56:56,120 --> 00:56:57,590
- I changed the title.

1215
00:56:57,590 --> 00:56:59,233
Sinner's Cafe seemed too obscure.

1216
00:57:00,310 --> 00:57:02,070
Oh, and you know, I do
have something for you.

1217
00:57:02,070 --> 00:57:03,910
This part says "orge Sand".

1218
00:57:03,910 --> 00:57:05,053
I figure it's yours?

1219
00:57:08,660 --> 00:57:09,493
- Oops.

1220
00:57:14,790 --> 00:57:16,190
Rosemary, I...

1221
00:57:17,100 --> 00:57:18,203
Can I sit down?
- No.

1222
00:57:22,520 --> 00:57:23,353
- Rosemary.

1223
00:57:26,210 --> 00:57:30,370
I'm sorry I broke into your
editing room, but I had to.

1224
00:57:30,370 --> 00:57:31,963
I'm a documentary filmmaker.

1225
00:57:35,540 --> 00:57:37,203
Rosemary, I've seen your film.

1226
00:57:38,150 --> 00:57:39,320
I know that it implicates you

1227
00:57:39,320 --> 00:57:41,140
in the murder of William Butler.

1228
00:57:41,140 --> 00:57:42,490
- Don't sell it short.

1229
00:57:42,490 --> 00:57:44,520
It does a whole hell of
a lot more than that.

1230
00:57:44,520 --> 00:57:46,910
- Rosemary, I want to believe
you're innocent, I really do,

1231
00:57:46,910 --> 00:57:48,360
but, as a documentary filmmaker,

1232
00:57:48,360 --> 00:57:50,590
I have to believe the
evidence that I've collected.

1233
00:57:50,590 --> 00:57:52,270
- It doesn't matter what you believe,

1234
00:57:52,270 --> 00:57:53,570
or what anyone else believes.

1235
00:57:54,600 --> 00:57:56,630
After tonight, it'll all be over.

1236
00:57:56,630 --> 00:57:58,670
- If you know that your
film implicates you,

1237
00:57:58,670 --> 00:58:00,020
why won't you pull it from the festival?

1238
00:58:00,020 --> 00:58:02,290
Do you need the prize money that badly?

1239
00:58:02,290 --> 00:58:04,650
- Oh, yeah, I need the
money so I can buy myself

1240
00:58:04,650 --> 00:58:06,123
some nice prison clothes.

1241
00:58:06,980 --> 00:58:09,890
- Then why don't you pull
it from the festival?

1242
00:58:09,890 --> 00:58:11,020
Otherwise--
- Don't you think

1243
00:58:11,020 --> 00:58:12,290
I want to pull it?

1244
00:58:12,290 --> 00:58:14,870
Don't you think I know it implicates me?

1245
00:58:14,870 --> 00:58:17,777
What kind of a fucking
moron do you take me for?!

1246
00:58:19,580 --> 00:58:22,053
- Um, those are all
rhetorical questions, right?

1247
00:58:23,003 --> 00:58:25,003
(sighs)

1248
00:58:26,250 --> 00:58:28,420
Then why won't you do it?!

1249
00:58:28,420 --> 00:58:31,963
- Two words: artistic fucking integrity.

1250
00:58:39,270 --> 00:58:41,500
- Well, that seemed to settle it.

1251
00:58:41,500 --> 00:58:43,960
I'd allowed my personal feelings
to interfere with my work,

1252
00:58:43,960 --> 00:58:45,710
but it had had no effect.

1253
00:58:45,710 --> 00:58:47,650
My documentary was like a runaway train

1254
00:58:47,650 --> 00:58:49,549
traveling toward somewhere
I did not want to go,

1255
00:58:49,549 --> 00:58:50,450
and there was no getting off

1256
00:58:50,450 --> 00:58:52,110
until we reached our final destination.

1257
00:58:52,110 --> 00:58:54,900
Here at the Second Annual
Mike Wong Film Festival,

1258
00:58:54,900 --> 00:58:58,270
the stars of the independent
film world are out in force.

1259
00:58:58,270 --> 00:58:59,703
There's what's-his-name.

1260
00:59:01,090 --> 00:59:03,383
There's that bloke who made that film.

1261
00:59:03,383 --> 00:59:04,630
And there's that woman
who wrote that script

1262
00:59:04,630 --> 00:59:06,750
that Bruce Willis almost did.

1263
00:59:06,750 --> 00:59:08,913
And, of course, Harvey Weinstein is here.

1264
00:59:10,620 --> 00:59:13,620
- The Mike Wong Film
Festival is an elitist sham!

1265
00:59:13,620 --> 00:59:14,940
If you really want to see the cutting edge

1266
00:59:14,940 --> 00:59:16,810
of current cinema, you
should come next door

1267
00:59:16,810 --> 00:59:18,240
to the Mike Dong Film Festival.

1268
00:59:18,240 --> 00:59:19,120
- Excuse me.

1269
00:59:19,120 --> 00:59:20,983
- No, I will not be silenced!

1270
00:59:20,983 --> 00:59:22,474
Vive la difference!

1271
00:59:22,474 --> 00:59:23,741
Vive Le Roi!

1272
00:59:23,741 --> 00:59:25,157
Apres moi, le deluge!

1273
00:59:25,157 --> 00:59:26,540
- I don't wish to silence you.

1274
00:59:26,540 --> 00:59:27,840
I'd like to interview you.

1275
00:59:28,860 --> 00:59:29,820
- Oh, I'm sorry.

1276
00:59:29,820 --> 00:59:32,130
- So, are you Mike Dong?

1277
00:59:32,130 --> 00:59:33,610
- No.

1278
00:59:33,610 --> 00:59:34,930
- Who is Mike Dong?

1279
00:59:34,930 --> 00:59:36,290
- There is no Mike Dong.

1280
00:59:36,290 --> 00:59:37,950
I just thought it was a good pun.

1281
00:59:37,950 --> 00:59:39,400
Mike Dong Festival

1282
00:59:39,400 --> 00:59:40,300
- I see.

1283
00:59:40,300 --> 00:59:42,190
I take it you've started this festival

1284
00:59:42,190 --> 00:59:44,810
as a protest to the
Mike Wong Film Festival.

1285
00:59:44,810 --> 00:59:45,660
- That's right.

1286
00:59:45,660 --> 00:59:48,430
My film didn't get into
the Mike Wong Festival,

1287
00:59:48,430 --> 00:59:50,000
probably because I'm from New Jersey,

1288
00:59:50,000 --> 00:59:52,890
where we don't have any elephants!

1289
00:59:52,890 --> 00:59:54,010
- [George] Thank you!

1290
00:59:54,010 --> 00:59:55,440
- Hey, you know the media's always welcome

1291
00:59:55,440 --> 00:59:56,913
at the Mike Dong Festival!

1292
00:59:58,200 --> 00:59:59,523
I'll leave you passes!

1293
01:00:00,400 --> 01:00:01,623
Anyone want passes?

1294
01:00:07,660 --> 01:00:09,560
- Excuse me, Mr. Dong.

1295
01:00:09,560 --> 01:00:11,120
- Wong.

1296
01:00:11,120 --> 01:00:12,510
- Uh, right.

1297
01:00:12,510 --> 01:00:14,000
What are the police doing here?

1298
01:00:14,000 --> 01:00:15,070
- I don't know, George.

1299
01:00:15,070 --> 01:00:17,700
They claim that someone
asked them to be here.

1300
01:00:17,700 --> 01:00:18,550
It wasn't me, though.

1301
01:00:22,680 --> 01:00:24,280
- What are you doing?

1302
01:00:24,280 --> 01:00:25,940
- I'm shooting a documentary.

1303
01:00:25,940 --> 01:00:27,793
- No, I'm shooting a documentary.

1304
01:00:28,970 --> 01:00:31,570
- I'm shooting a documentary
about your documentary.

1305
01:00:33,240 --> 01:00:34,073
- Great.

1306
01:00:36,529 --> 01:00:37,362
(audience applauds)

1307
01:00:37,362 --> 01:00:39,580
- [George Voiceover] The moment
of truth was nearly upon us.

1308
01:00:39,580 --> 01:00:41,140
One thing was certain:

1309
01:00:41,140 --> 01:00:43,400
After Rosemary's film,
the first prize winner

1310
01:00:43,400 --> 01:00:46,840
would be announced, and
perhaps the killer, as well.

1311
01:00:46,840 --> 01:00:49,130
- So, without further ado,

1312
01:00:49,130 --> 01:00:50,930
I'd like to bring on Rosemary Olsen,

1313
01:00:50,930 --> 01:00:53,320
the director of tonight's short film,

1314
01:00:53,320 --> 01:00:56,390
"Black Roses, Black
Carnations, Black Daisies".

1315
01:00:56,390 --> 01:00:59,753
Rosemary?
(audience applauds)

1316
01:01:01,463 --> 01:01:04,897
- I think it was Orson
Welles who once asked,

1317
01:01:04,897 --> 01:01:06,707
"What the hell was I thinking?"

1318
01:01:08,050 --> 01:01:08,883
Thank you.

1319
01:01:11,832 --> 01:01:13,364
(film projector clicking)

1320
01:01:13,364 --> 01:01:16,364
(smoky jazz music)

1321
01:01:33,240 --> 01:01:36,733
- With this elephant, I thee kill.

1322
01:01:37,860 --> 01:01:39,393
- That is so weird.

1323
01:01:40,280 --> 01:01:42,800
That's exactly how that
Maria woman was killed.

1324
01:01:42,800 --> 01:01:44,260
- Cut the camera, Tori.

1325
01:01:44,260 --> 01:01:46,740
- George, you're letting
your personal feelings

1326
01:01:46,740 --> 01:01:48,230
get in the way here.

1327
01:01:48,230 --> 01:01:49,660
Remember who you are.

1328
01:01:49,660 --> 01:01:51,144
Be a professional.

1329
01:01:51,144 --> 01:01:53,727
(George sighs)

1330
01:01:56,738 --> 01:01:59,071
(gun fires)

1331
01:02:01,935 --> 01:02:02,935
- I'm sorry.

1332
01:02:04,250 --> 01:02:05,163
I didn't mean to.

1333
01:02:21,016 --> 01:02:21,849
Whoops.

1334
01:02:26,780 --> 01:02:27,613
I'm sorry.

1335
01:02:29,100 --> 01:02:32,013
But I didn't kill you, your film did.

1336
01:02:53,369 --> 01:02:56,450
- I don't know what to say, Rosemary.

1337
01:02:56,450 --> 01:02:57,820
- [Detective Blank] Excuse me, Mr. Wong.

1338
01:02:57,820 --> 01:02:59,370
- [Arthur] Yes, Detective.

1339
01:02:59,370 --> 01:03:01,490
- I may not know a lot about movies--

1340
01:03:01,490 --> 01:03:03,363
- About film, Detective.

1341
01:03:04,430 --> 01:03:05,323
- About film.

1342
01:03:06,210 --> 01:03:09,130
Maybe I'm just a cop who
found Tarkovsky's last films

1343
01:03:09,130 --> 01:03:13,183
too dry and pedantic, but
I do know what my duty is.

1344
01:03:15,000 --> 01:03:17,923
You have the cinematic flair
of a master, Miss Olsen.

1345
01:03:20,170 --> 01:03:22,120
And you have the right to remain silent.

1346
01:03:22,120 --> 01:03:25,420
- You don't understand,
my film is anti-violence.

1347
01:03:25,420 --> 01:03:26,970
- Tell it to the critics, lady.

1348
01:03:31,630 --> 01:03:33,010
- Detective, don't you think

1349
01:03:33,010 --> 01:03:35,010
this is censorship of the worst degree?

1350
01:03:35,010 --> 01:03:35,843
You're arresting this woman

1351
01:03:35,843 --> 01:03:37,510
because you didn't like her film.

1352
01:03:37,510 --> 01:03:39,510
- I loved her film.

1353
01:03:39,510 --> 01:03:41,950
But it proves that she
murdered those other directors.

1354
01:03:41,950 --> 01:03:43,340
- Just because her film is about killing

1355
01:03:43,340 --> 01:03:45,010
doesn't make her a murderer.

1356
01:03:45,010 --> 01:03:48,180
By that token, Martin
Scorsese would be a gangster,

1357
01:03:48,180 --> 01:03:50,240
and Woody Allen would be, um...

1358
01:03:52,210 --> 01:03:53,233
Oh, never mind.

1359
01:03:54,450 --> 01:03:55,283
- Rosemary!

1360
01:03:56,570 --> 01:03:58,140
I think you should know that your film

1361
01:03:58,140 --> 01:04:00,310
was going to be awarded first place.

1362
01:04:00,310 --> 01:04:02,900
But, given these developments,

1363
01:04:02,900 --> 01:04:05,810
we have to award the money
to the first runner-up.

1364
01:04:05,810 --> 01:04:07,063
Congratulations, George.

1365
01:04:08,070 --> 01:04:10,550
I only wish I'd seen her film earlier.

1366
01:04:10,550 --> 01:04:13,350
Perhaps some of these murders
could have been prevented.

1367
01:04:15,020 --> 01:04:16,620
- Hold on a second!

1368
01:04:16,620 --> 01:04:19,090
Mr. Wong, who judged Rosemary's film?

1369
01:04:19,090 --> 01:04:21,240
- Well, I recused myself

1370
01:04:21,240 --> 01:04:23,770
because Rosemary and my son were close,

1371
01:04:23,770 --> 01:04:25,520
and I don't believe Siobhan

1372
01:04:25,520 --> 01:04:27,737
actually watched any of the films,

1373
01:04:27,737 --> 01:04:29,680
that means Elephant,

1374
01:04:29,680 --> 01:04:31,832
Elliot was the only judge to see it.

1375
01:04:31,832 --> 01:04:34,596
- And Elliot's film is next
on the schedule, isn't it?

1376
01:04:34,596 --> 01:04:36,210
I think we should watch it right now.

1377
01:04:36,210 --> 01:04:37,900
- Do you think I'm crazy?

1378
01:04:37,900 --> 01:04:39,070
Look what happened to the last director

1379
01:04:39,070 --> 01:04:39,970
who showed a film here.

1380
01:04:39,970 --> 01:04:42,083
- Elephant, your award stipulated
that you would have to--

1381
01:04:42,083 --> 01:04:44,670
- I'm not gonna show my
film with any cops around.

1382
01:04:44,670 --> 01:04:47,040
They take these things too literally!

1383
01:04:47,040 --> 01:04:48,260
And stop calling me Elephant.

1384
01:04:48,260 --> 01:04:51,257
- Elliot, you're gonna give me that film,

1385
01:04:51,257 --> 01:04:53,220
and we're gonna watch it.

1386
01:04:53,220 --> 01:04:55,960
- Careful, George, you're
becoming part of the story.

1387
01:04:55,960 --> 01:04:56,963
- Screw the story.

1388
01:04:57,990 --> 01:04:59,541
This has to do with the truth.

1389
01:04:59,541 --> 01:05:02,960
(suspenseful music)

1390
01:05:02,960 --> 01:05:05,793
(thrilling music)

1391
01:05:21,762 --> 01:05:22,595
(footsteps patter)

1392
01:05:22,595 --> 01:05:24,223
I'll take that film now, Elliot.

1393
01:05:26,285 --> 01:05:27,690
- How dare you.

1394
01:05:27,690 --> 01:05:29,443
You, a filmmaker yourself.

1395
01:05:29,443 --> 01:05:31,927
This is my film, I created it,

1396
01:05:31,927 --> 01:05:34,240
and I don't think the current
climate is right for it!

1397
01:05:34,240 --> 01:05:37,320
- You knew the rules when
you took the money, Elliot.

1398
01:05:37,320 --> 01:05:40,420
A year later you were gonna
have to screen the film.

1399
01:05:40,420 --> 01:05:41,273
Time's up.

1400
01:05:44,043 --> 01:05:46,320
Do the right thing, Elliot.

1401
01:05:46,320 --> 01:05:47,650
- Never!

1402
01:05:47,650 --> 01:05:50,817
(microphone clacking)

1403
01:05:56,224 --> 01:05:58,555
The medium is the message!

1404
01:05:58,555 --> 01:05:59,932
- [Tori] Hey, I said that.

1405
01:05:59,932 --> 01:06:02,010
- Besides, you have to speak

1406
01:06:02,010 --> 01:06:05,120
into the microphone!
(microphone thuds)

1407
01:06:07,650 --> 01:06:08,760
You get all that?

1408
01:06:08,760 --> 01:06:10,057
- Yeah, I got it.

1409
01:06:10,954 --> 01:06:12,854
But I don't think the sound is usable.

1410
01:06:17,638 --> 01:06:18,800
- [George Voiceover] For the last time,

1411
01:06:18,800 --> 01:06:20,760
we all gathered in the theater,

1412
01:06:20,760 --> 01:06:22,590
watching the screen for answers,

1413
01:06:22,590 --> 01:06:24,440
hoping that the auteur theory

1414
01:06:24,440 --> 01:06:26,523
had one last trick up its sleeves.

1415
01:06:27,586 --> 01:06:31,670
(film projector clicking)

1416
01:06:31,670 --> 01:06:33,770
- Once upon a time, there was a filmmaker.

1417
01:06:34,610 --> 01:06:37,823
This filmmaker was thought
by some to be a genius.

1418
01:06:37,823 --> 01:06:42,823
(children yelling)
(ominous atonal music)

1419
01:07:09,659 --> 01:07:11,027
(gun fires)

1420
01:07:11,027 --> 01:07:13,944
(people screaming)

1421
01:07:17,342 --> 01:07:19,472
- Why did you kill him?

1422
01:07:19,472 --> 01:07:21,920
(static crackling)

1423
01:07:21,920 --> 01:07:25,960
- Yes, some people thought
this filmmaker was a genius.

1424
01:07:25,960 --> 01:07:27,700
And not only did he have talent,

1425
01:07:27,700 --> 01:07:31,360
he had money, money to
make a feature film.

1426
01:07:31,360 --> 01:07:34,710
But, try as he might, this
prodigiously talented filmmaker

1427
01:07:34,710 --> 01:07:38,073
could not find a topic
for his feature film.

1428
01:07:40,140 --> 01:07:41,940
Until one day...

1429
01:07:41,940 --> 01:07:45,070
The filmmaker was judging some
short films for a festival,

1430
01:07:45,070 --> 01:07:47,130
while being watched by
one of his classmates,

1431
01:07:47,130 --> 01:07:49,490
a promiscuous Latina filmmaker.

1432
01:07:49,490 --> 01:07:52,980
- Look at you, judging
other people's movies,

1433
01:07:52,980 --> 01:07:54,980
and you don't have an idea for your own.

1434
01:07:56,190 --> 01:08:00,053
Any real artist would know
what to do with that money.

1435
01:08:01,790 --> 01:08:03,060
I can't believe I've been sleeping

1436
01:08:03,060 --> 01:08:05,143
with such an ineffectual putz.

1437
01:08:06,650 --> 01:08:08,020
Why don't you use that money

1438
01:08:08,020 --> 01:08:11,000
to buy yourself a really nice gun,

1439
01:08:11,000 --> 01:08:12,433
and shoot yourself with it?

1440
01:08:13,270 --> 01:08:15,940
Or give me the money, and I'll shoot you,

1441
01:08:15,940 --> 01:08:17,350
you pathetic, little man!

1442
01:08:17,350 --> 01:08:18,276
- Shut up!
(loud thud)

1443
01:08:18,276 --> 01:08:21,026
(dramatic music)

1444
01:08:23,741 --> 01:08:27,057
(smoky jazz music)

1445
01:08:31,539 --> 01:08:34,372
- With this elephant, I thee kill.

1446
01:08:37,097 --> 01:08:39,810
- And then, inspiration.

1447
01:08:39,810 --> 01:08:42,090
He would make a film about murder,

1448
01:08:42,090 --> 01:08:45,310
or, more accurately, he
would make a film about film.

1449
01:08:45,310 --> 01:08:47,810
The filmmaker knew that for
this film to be true to life,

1450
01:08:47,810 --> 01:08:49,660
it would have to be
patterned on real life,

1451
01:08:49,660 --> 01:08:51,310
like his earlier work.

1452
01:08:51,310 --> 01:08:55,230
So-called "real life"
would be reproduced on film

1453
01:08:55,230 --> 01:08:57,810
with younger, more attractive actors.

1454
01:08:57,810 --> 01:09:00,300
But, in this case, a
further wrinkle was added:

1455
01:09:00,300 --> 01:09:01,490
The source film would first

1456
01:09:01,490 --> 01:09:03,240
have to be replicated in real life

1457
01:09:03,240 --> 01:09:05,460
so that real life could then be reproduced

1458
01:09:05,460 --> 01:09:06,503
in the final film.

1459
01:09:08,160 --> 01:09:11,813
Film inspiring reality inspiring film.

1460
01:09:12,840 --> 01:09:16,111
It was all so beautifully

1461
01:09:16,111 --> 01:09:17,169
postmodern

1462
01:09:18,530 --> 01:09:21,730
As in any collaboration,
there was occasional tension.

1463
01:09:21,730 --> 01:09:23,671
- [Bad Chinese accent]
You keep film in festival,

1464
01:09:23,671 --> 01:09:25,004
or I kill again!

1465
01:09:25,004 --> 01:09:25,980
- I can't!

1466
01:09:25,980 --> 01:09:27,490
You're framing me for murder!

1467
01:09:27,490 --> 01:09:28,560
- [Teen Elliot] You keep in,

1468
01:09:28,560 --> 01:09:33,043
or you have more deaths on
your hands, like Mike's.

1469
01:09:34,234 --> 01:09:37,830
- Who are you, you cruel, heartless boy?

1470
01:09:37,830 --> 01:09:39,230
Who are you?!

1471
01:09:39,230 --> 01:09:40,371
- I am...

1472
01:09:42,788 --> 01:09:44,021
Art.

1473
01:09:45,370 --> 01:09:47,713
My name is Art.

1474
01:09:51,260 --> 01:09:54,627
("La Marseillaise")

1475
01:10:03,527 --> 01:10:06,444
(people murmuring)

1476
01:10:11,710 --> 01:10:13,055
- Let's go, Elephant.

1477
01:10:14,620 --> 01:10:16,560
- You people are such literalists!

1478
01:10:16,560 --> 01:10:18,290
Didn't you read the disclaimer?

1479
01:10:18,290 --> 01:10:21,330
- I'm a firm believer in the
doctrine of intentionality.

1480
01:10:21,330 --> 01:10:22,980
- Do you discount Foucault?

1481
01:10:22,980 --> 01:10:24,730
- Well, I don't discount him,

1482
01:10:24,730 --> 01:10:27,220
I simply find his conclusions reductive.

1483
01:10:27,220 --> 01:10:29,320
- Hmm, well, I've tried to reconcile

1484
01:10:29,320 --> 01:10:31,400
the theories of Lacan with Foucault

1485
01:10:31,400 --> 01:10:32,720
and the other major deconstructionists,

1486
01:10:32,720 --> 01:10:34,660
and I find, ultimately, it
leads me to the conclusion:

1487
01:10:34,660 --> 01:10:35,493
I must kill.

1488
01:10:35,493 --> 01:10:37,000
- Really?

1489
01:10:37,000 --> 01:10:38,582
- Detective, I think this is the beginning

1490
01:10:38,582 --> 01:10:40,270
of a beautiful friendship.

1491
01:10:40,270 --> 01:10:42,160
- I knew all along that he was the killer.

1492
01:10:42,160 --> 01:10:43,660
Never a doubt in my mind.

1493
01:10:43,660 --> 01:10:45,240
- Right, right. Wow.

1494
01:10:45,240 --> 01:10:47,970
- Next year, I'm entering
the Mike Dong Festival.

1495
01:10:47,970 --> 01:10:49,010
- I hear that.

1496
01:10:49,010 --> 01:10:50,410
This festival is not

1497
01:10:50,410 --> 01:10:51,540
what it used to be.
- My next film will be

1498
01:10:51,540 --> 01:10:52,540
about a great white whale

1499
01:10:52,540 --> 01:10:53,477
that wears a paper bag on its head,

1500
01:10:53,477 --> 01:10:55,327
and the captain who's
obsessed with catching him.

1501
01:10:55,327 --> 01:10:58,352
- And the captain wears a
paper back on his head, too?

1502
01:10:58,352 --> 01:10:59,560
- [Unknown Filmmaker] No,
that's where I take it all

1503
01:10:59,560 --> 01:11:00,560
to the next level.

1504
01:11:00,560 --> 01:11:03,950
The captain wears a
plastic bag on his head.

1505
01:11:03,950 --> 01:11:05,540
- Oh, that's brilliant.

1506
01:11:05,540 --> 01:11:08,900
Hey, I can guarantee you a
slot in my festival next year!

1507
01:11:08,900 --> 01:11:09,733
Hey!

1508
01:11:15,270 --> 01:11:18,500
- You can't blame yourself
for what happened to Mike.

1509
01:11:18,500 --> 01:11:19,550
- I know I shouldn't.

1510
01:11:20,630 --> 01:11:23,510
And it helped to express
my feelings in the movie.

1511
01:11:23,510 --> 01:11:25,490
We filmmakers, we use our movies

1512
01:11:25,490 --> 01:11:28,120
as substitutes for psychotherapy.

1513
01:11:28,120 --> 01:11:29,253
Costs about the same.

1514
01:11:30,290 --> 01:11:33,420
- Rosemary, I'm terribly sorry.

1515
01:11:33,420 --> 01:11:35,503
Of course, first prize is yours.

1516
01:11:36,750 --> 01:11:38,830
I'm sure you understand, George.

1517
01:11:38,830 --> 01:11:41,590
- My work's not suited
to features, anyway.

1518
01:11:41,590 --> 01:11:43,390
- Thank you, Mr. Wong.

1519
01:11:43,390 --> 01:11:44,903
I accept in memory of Mike.

1520
01:11:48,930 --> 01:11:51,920
- And so, matters came
to a happy conclusion.

1521
01:11:51,920 --> 01:11:54,210
True, Detective Blank's
interpretation of Elliot's film

1522
01:11:54,210 --> 01:11:57,320
was a bit blunt, but,
well, he was a believer

1523
01:11:57,320 --> 01:12:00,390
in the doctrine of
intentionality, after all.

1524
01:12:00,390 --> 01:12:03,163
As for me, I learned an important lesson:

1525
01:12:04,050 --> 01:12:06,733
sometimes a film is just a film.

1526
01:12:09,410 --> 01:12:12,200
- So, whatever happened to you and--

1527
01:12:12,200 --> 01:12:13,243
- Miss Olsen?

1528
01:12:14,640 --> 01:12:15,473
- Well...

1529
01:12:16,450 --> 01:12:18,410
- I think you know that I consider you

1530
01:12:18,410 --> 01:12:19,913
more than just a subject.

1531
01:12:22,360 --> 01:12:23,430
- I know, George.

1532
01:12:24,890 --> 01:12:29,423
- I wonder if you might
consider a collaboration.

1533
01:12:31,570 --> 01:12:35,373
- What sort of a collaboration
did you have in mind?

1534
01:12:35,373 --> 01:12:38,043
- A very close collaboration.

1535
01:12:41,115 --> 01:12:43,377
- I could be open to that possibility.

1536
01:12:50,530 --> 01:12:52,083
Of course, I get top billing.

1537
01:12:53,608 --> 01:12:54,441
- Of course.

1538
01:13:04,172 --> 01:13:05,920
(sighs)

1539
01:13:05,920 --> 01:13:07,910
Well, there you have it.

1540
01:13:07,910 --> 01:13:11,650
- I'll grant you, Mr.
Sand, you spin a nice tale.

1541
01:13:11,650 --> 01:13:13,650
But, unfortunately for you,

1542
01:13:13,650 --> 01:13:16,843
I've seen some footage that
tells a very different story.

1543
01:13:18,396 --> 01:13:20,263
Would you please show
in the other gentleman?

1544
01:13:28,980 --> 01:13:29,813
- Sorry.

1545
01:13:30,920 --> 01:13:32,670
I needed finishing funds too.

1546
01:13:39,780 --> 01:13:40,613
- So?

1547
01:13:45,360 --> 01:13:47,350
- [George] There, there, Tori.

1548
01:13:47,350 --> 01:13:49,514
We'll find an audience for our film.

1549
01:13:49,514 --> 01:13:51,140
- [Tori] But where?

1550
01:13:51,140 --> 01:13:53,983
- [George] A place where the
people are truly open-minded.

1551
01:13:54,880 --> 01:13:55,713
America.

1552
01:13:57,030 --> 01:13:58,263
- [Tori] Or Canada?

1553
01:13:59,590 --> 01:14:00,965
- [George] Or Canada.

1554
01:14:03,380 --> 01:14:05,072
- [Tori] What about Chad?

1555
01:14:07,680 --> 01:14:10,763
(apprehensive music)

1556
01:15:10,210 --> 01:15:12,793
(upbeat music)

1557
01:15:37,514 --> 01:15:40,097
(gentle music)

1558
01:16:14,436 --> 01:16:17,436
(suspenseful music)
